Sure, here's an example remote monitoring script that uses PowerShell remoting to monitor the status of a list of servers:


```perl
# List of servers to monitor
$servers = "server1", "server2", "server3"

# Loop through servers and check status
foreach ($server in $servers) {
 # Test connection to server
 if (Test-Connection -ComputerName $server -Count 1 -Quiet) {
 # Get status of critical services
 $services = Get-Service -ComputerName $server -DisplayName "Windows Firewall", "Server", "Workstation"

 # Check status of services
 $firewallStatus = $services | Where-Object {$_.DisplayName -eq "Windows Firewall"} | Select-Object -ExpandProperty Status
 $serverStatus = $services | Where-Object {$_.DisplayName -eq "Server"} | Select-Object -ExpandProperty Status
 $workstationStatus = $services | Where-Object {$_.DisplayName -eq "Workstation"} | Select-Object -ExpandProperty Status

 # Check if all services are running
 if ($firewallStatus -eq "Running" -and $serverStatus -eq "Running" -and $workstationStatus -eq "Running") {
 Write-Host "$server: All critical services are running." -ForegroundColor Green
 }
 else {
 Write-Host "$server: Critical services are not running." -ForegroundColor Red
 }
 }
 else {
 Write-Host "$server: Connection failed." -ForegroundColor Red
 }
}
```
This script first defines a list of servers to monitor, and then loops through each server to check its status. For each server, the script first tests the connection to the server using the `Test-Connection` cmdlet. If the connection is successful, the script then retrieves the status of critical services using the `Get-Service` cmdlet. The script then checks the status of the Windows Firewall, Server, and Workstation services, and writes a message to the console indicating whether all services are running or not.

Note that this is just an example script, and you may need to modify it to suit your specific needs and environment. Also, make sure to test the script thoroughly before running it on production systems. Finally, make sure to enable PowerShell remoting on the target servers before running the script.

