public List<User> getUsers() {
 List<User> users = userService.getAllUsers();
 return users;
}
```
`@RequestBody` is used to indicate that the incoming HTTP request should be deserialized into an object, rather than being interpreted as separate request parameters. This annotation is typically used in conjunction with a RESTful API, where the client sends a request body containing data to be processed by the server.

For example, if you have a method in a controller that expects a JSON object as input, you can annotate the method parameter with `@RequestBody` and Spring will automatically deserialize the JSON into an object of the specified type.


```java
