The issue is that the `onChange` function is using the variable `i` which is defined in the outer scope. This variable is being re-assigned in each iteration of the loop so by the time the event listener is invoked the value of `i` is the last value it was assigned to in the loop.

To fix this, you can use an arrow function to capture the value of `i` at the time the event listener is added, or you can use the `let` keyword instead of `var` so that `i` is block-scoped instead of function-scoped.

Here is an example of using an arrow function to fix the issue:


```c
heckbox.addEventListener("change", () => {
 var title = cells[i].nextElementSibling.nextElementSibling.textContent;
 title = title.trim();
 if (this.checked) {
 label.textContent = "✔";
 data[title] = true;
 } else {
 label.textContent = "Watched";
 data[title] = false;
 }
 localStorage.setItem("data", JSON.stringify(data));
});
```
And here is an example of using the `let` keyword to fix the issue:


```
for (let i = 0; i < cells.length; i++) {
 // rest of the code
}
```

The problem is that the `this` keyword inside the `onchange` event listener callback function refers to the checkbox element, not to the `cells[i]` variable. When the loop finishes executing, the `i` variable will have the last value assigned to it and `cells[i]` will refer to the last cell element in the loop. So when the event listener callback function is invoked, `cells[i]` will not be the cell element corresponding to the checkbox that was clicked.

You can solve this issue by using closures or by storing the cell element in the checkbox element itself.

Here is an example of how you can use closures to solve the problem:


```
for (var i = 0; i < cells.length; i++) {
 // ...
 checkbox.addEventListener("change", (function(cell) {
 return function() {
 var title = cell.nextElementSibling.nextElementSibling.textContent;
 title = title.trim();
 if (this.checked) {
 label.textContent = "✔";
 data[title] = true;
 } else {
 label.textContent = "Watched";
 data[title] = false;
 }
 localStorage.setItem("data", JSON.stringify(data));
 }
 })(cells[i]));
}
```
Here, in the event listener, we are creating a function that takes the cell as an argument, and returns another function. So when the returned function is invoked, it has access to the cell variable that was passed in, which is the cell element corresponding to the checkbox that was clicked.

